A couple things to note - a sample size of just over 500 is pretty dismal. We should take all results with a grain of salt here. Other than that, the only fishy thing we notice is some outliers in the price variable.

Price seems like a good variable to use as a target in our regression models - let's take a look at it's distribution.

In [59]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))

This looks like a fairly normal distribution, but we're seeing those outliers on the right hand side. We'll want to keep that in mind through our analysis.

For the classification problem, it would be interesting to predict the variable CHAS, which is a dummy variable that tells us if the tract borders the Charles River. Let's take a look and see how balanced this variable is.

It looks like our target variable is unbalanced, so we should not trust accuracy scores - instead, we'll look at F1 scores to determine how well our classification models are doing.

Let's check out our correlation matrix before we start running the models.

In [63]:
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(25,8)})
sns.set_context("talk", font_scale=0.7)
sns.heatmap(df.iloc[:,1:].corr(), annot=True)
Out[63]:
<AxesSubplot:>

There's a good bit of correlation going on between our variables, but nothing very surprising. The distance from the 5 Boston employment centres (DIS) is highly and negatively correlated with the proportion of non-retail business acres (INDUS), the nitric oxides concentration (NOX), and the proportion of homes built before 1940 (AGE). These are all things that we would expect to increase as we get closer to the city. As for the variables we're most interested in, we can see that price is highly and negatively correlated with the % of lower status of the population (LSTAT) and highly and positively correlated with the average number of rooms per dwelling (RM) which is also not surprising as we would expect more expensive homes to be bigger and in areas with a higher median income. Our classification target variable, CHAS, is not highly correlated with any other variable.

Regression Problem¶

For our regression problem, we are going to use the supervised models to predict the price variable (median value of owner occupied homes in the tract) based on the other features in the dataset.

def my_polynomial_regression(poly_degree, X, y, test_size=0.3, rand_state=100):
    
    poly_features= PolynomialFeatures(degree=poly_degree)
    
    # transforms the existing features to higher degree features.
    X = poly_features.fit_transform(df_sc)  
    
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=rand_state)
    
    # fit the transformed features to Linear Regression
    polynomial_model = LinearRegression()
    polynomial_model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    
  
    # predicting on training data-set
    y_train_predicted= polynomial_model.predict(X_train)
  
    # predicting on test data-set
    y_test_predicted = polynomial_model.predict(X_test)
  
   # evaluating the model on training dataset
    MSE_train = round(np.mean(np.square(y_train - y_train_predicted)),2)
    RMSE_train = round(np.sqrt(MSE_train),2)

  
    # evaluating the model on test dataset
    MSE_test = round(np.mean(np.square(y_test - y_test_predicted)),2)
    RMSE_test = round(np.sqrt(MSE_test),7)


  
#     print("Traning model fit")
#     print("R2_train = {}".format(R2_train))

#     print("-------------------------------------------")
#     print("MSE_train = {}".format(MSE_train))
#     print("RMSE_train = {}".format(RMSE_train))

#     print("-------------------------------------------")
#     print("MSE_test = {}".format(MSE_test))
#     print("RMSE_test = {}".format(RMSE_test))
    
    return poly_degree, RMSE_train, RMSE_test

RMSE_CV=[]
RMSE_test = []

k=40

for i in range(1,k):
    KNN_i = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=i)
    KNN_i.fit(X_train, y_train)
    RMSE_i = np.sqrt(np.mean(-1*cross_val_score(estimator = KNN_i, X = X_train, y = y_train, cv = 10 , scoring="neg_mean_squared_error" )))
    RMSE_CV.append(RMSE_i)
    
    RMSE_test.append(np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(y_test - KNN_i.predict(X_test)))))
    
optimal_k = pd.DataFrame({'RMSE_CV': np.round(RMSE_CV,2), 'RMSE_test':np.round(RMSE_test,2)}, index=range(1,k))

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, recall_score, precision_score, f1_score



def my_logistic_report(X_train, y_train, X_test,y_test, threshold=0.15): # you could make it even more general!
    logistic= LogisticRegression()
    logistic.fit(X_train, y_train)
    probs = logistic.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    y_hat = np.where(probs>=threshold,1,0)
    
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_hat)
    accuracy = round(accuracy_score(y_test,y_hat) ,2)
    precision = round(precision_score(y_test,y_hat),2)
    recall = round(recall_score(y_test,y_hat),2)
    f1score = round(f1_score(y_test,y_hat),2)
    cm_labled = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=['Actual : negative ','Actual : positive'], columns=['Predict : negative','Predict :positive '])
    
    print("-----------------------------------------")
    print('Accuracy  = {}'.format(accuracy))
    print('Precision = {}'.format(precision))
    print('Recall    = {}'.format(recall))
    print('f1_score  = {}'.format(f1score))
    print("-----------------------------------------")
    return cm_labled

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, recall_score, precision_score, f1_score



def my_KNN_report(X_train, y_train, X_test,y_test, K=5, threshold=0.5):
    knn= KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=K)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    probs = knn.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    y_hat = np.where(probs>=threshold,1,0)
    
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_hat)
    accuracy = round(accuracy_score(y_test,y_hat) ,4)
    error_rate = round(1-accuracy,4)
    precision = round(precision_score(y_test,y_hat),2)
    recall = round(recall_score(y_test,y_hat),2)
    f1score = round(f1_score(y_test,y_hat),2)
    cm_labled = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=['Actual : negative ','Actual : positive'], columns=['Predict : negative','Predict :positive '])
    
    print("-----------------------------------------")
    print('Accuracy  = {}'.format(accuracy))
    print('Error_rate  = {}'.format(error_rate))
    print('Precision = {}'.format(precision))
    print('Recall    = {}'.format(recall))
    print('f1_score  = {}'.format(f1score))
    print("-----------------------------------------")
    return cm_labled

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, recall_score, precision_score, f1_score



def my_SVM_report(X_train, y_train, X_test,y_test, C=1,gamma='scale' ,kernel='rbf'):
    svc= SVC(C=C, gamma=gamma, kernel=kernel)
    svc.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_hat = svc.predict(X_test)
    
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_hat)
    accuracy = round(accuracy_score(y_test,y_hat) ,4)
    error_rate = round(1-accuracy,4)
    precision = round(precision_score(y_test,y_hat),2)
    recall = round(recall_score(y_test,y_hat),2)
    f1score = round(f1_score(y_test,y_hat),2)
    cm_labled = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=['Actual : negative ','Actual : positive'], columns=['Predict : negative','Predict :positive '])
    
    print("-----------------------------------------")
    print('Accuracy  = {}'.format(accuracy))
    print('Error_rate  = {}'.format(error_rate))
    print('Precision = {}'.format(precision))
    print('Recall    = {}'.format(recall))
    print('f1_score  = {}'.format(f1score))
    print("-----------------------------------------")
    return cm_labled

For the regresion problem, it looks like the SVM model is best for predicting the price variable (median value of owner occupied homes in the tract). The polynomial model technically has the best RMSE, but we know better than to trust a perfect score; it's more likely that there's overfitting or something else that's causing the perfect score.

For the classification problem, KNN has the best F1 score and thus that model is best for predicting whether or not a tract is bordering the Charles River.
